On the other hand, `.equals()` is the method you should use to compare the values of two strings in Java. When you call `.equals()` on a string object, it compares the character sequences of the two strings lexicographically (character by character).

The situation where you encountered the bug was likely caused by using two different string objects with the same content. Although the strings seemed identical to you, they might have been created at different points in the program or through different methods. When you used `.equals()` instead, it compared the values of the strings, and since the contents were the same, it produced the expected result.

As a general rule, `==` should be used when comparing references to the same object, while `.equals()` should be used when comparing the values of objects, including strings. This is particularly important when it comes to strings in Java, since strings are immutable and are often created at different points in the program.

